body:
Consider this input:
```mlir
firrtl.circuit "Foo" attributes {annotations = [{
  class = "firrtl.transforms.MustDeduplicateAnnotation",
  modules = ["~Foo|Foo", "~Foo|Bar"]
}]} {
  firrtl.module @Foo() {
    %wire = firrtl.wire : !firrtl.rwprobe<uint<32>>
    %wire1 = firrtl.wire sym @sym : !firrtl.uint<32>
    %0 = firrtl.ref.rwprobe <@Foo::@sym> : !firrtl.rwprobe<uint<32>>
    %1 = firrtl.ref.cast %0 : (!firrtl.rwprobe<uint<32>>) -> !firrtl.rwprobe<uint<32>>
    firrtl.ref.define %wire, %1 : !firrtl.rwprobe<uint<32>>
  }
  firrtl.module private @Bar() {
    %wire = firrtl.wire : !firrtl.rwprobe<uint<32>>
    %wire1 = firrtl.wire sym @sym : !firrtl.uint<32>
    %0 = firrtl.ref.rwprobe <@Bar::@sym> : !firrtl.rwprobe<uint<32>>
    %1 = firrtl.ref.cast %0 : (!firrtl.rwprobe<uint<32>>) -> !firrtl.rwprobe<uint<32>>
    firrtl.ref.define %wire, %1 : !firrtl.rwprobe<uint<32>>
    %wire2 = firrtl.wire : !firrtl.uint<1>
  }
}
```
Running this through `circt-opt --firrtl-dedup` reports an error with the `@Foo::@sym` not being dedupable with `@Bar::@sym`. However, if I remove the `%wire2` which is only present in one module, dedup succeeds. This smells like dedup is failing because of the `%wire2`, but the pass then compares the two modules and erroneously thinks the symbol mismatch is the cause of the dedup failure.

